@TakuyaKanbara-d9r Not even close. Chuck Feeney gave away his stock in DFS group to charity in '84  and spent the next 26 years running the charity giving ~8 billion dollars until they dispersed the last of their funds in 2020. He did most of his charity anonymously intentionally to get donors who would pay more for naming rights to donate more money. When he closed down his charity in 2020 and then died last year it barely made the news, which is I think how he wanted it.

When I look through the list of what Feeney donated to I don't agree with every dollar being the best place to have donated money, but he certainly gave away a lot more a lot earlier than people like Rowling, he lived in his ~2 mm dollar house in SF (which is not an extravagant house in SF) and lived off something like ~3mm in investments he kept in his name until he died and left that bit to his wife.

Not all philanthropists want a public profile, most don't look for the attention of being a household name.

